[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi all, Long time since I've been here because of studies, but now I'm using roc for AoC!</p>\n<p>I found myself wanting a function like <code>List.mapAdjacent</code> a lot. Not just in AoC, but other situations as well. I just happened to want to use it in today's puzzle.</p>\n<p>For those who don't know what <code>mapAdjacent</code> is. It is found in a few utility libraries in haskell (so it can be found on hoogle), but I know it from c++ as adjacent_transform (because in c++, every map function must be named transform). It takes a <code>List a</code> and a binary function <code>a, a -&gt; b</code> and takes any two adjacent pairs in the list and applies the function to them.<br>\nFor example, <code>List.mapAdjacent [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] Num.add</code> would return <code>[3, 5, 7, 9]</code>. The resulting list's length is always one smaller than the input list's length. Only if the input was empty, the result is still empty.</p>\n<p>This can be implemented in pure roc as</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">dropFirst</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Every time I needed it in roc, I implemented something like this with the function filled in, but this does not work well in pipelines because you need the list twice. This is why I want it in the standard library.</p>\n<p>What do you guys think?</p>",
        "id": 406912843,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702113701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://hackage.haskell.org/package/utility-ht-0.0.17/docs/Data-List-HT.html#v:mapAdjacent\">link to haskell docs</a></p>",
        "id": 406914334,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1702114545
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was thinking about having a <code>List.windows</code> functions, similar to <a href=\"https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/primitive.slice.html#method.windows\">the one in Rust</a>. Then you could use it to achieve the same result</p>",
        "id": 406914488,
        "sender_full_name": "LoipesMas",
        "timestamp": 1702114580
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>True!<br>\nThe only difference is you then need to pipe it to a <a href=\"http://List.map\">List.map</a> with a function which takes a list as an input. Most of the times however, you know the length of that list beforehand (2 in mapAdjacent), so this makes it annoying to have to unpack it</p>",
        "id": 406914758,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702114746
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not against adding both List.mapAdjacent and <a href=\"http://List.windows\">List.windows</a> though</p>",
        "id": 406914802,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702114771
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have a working fork with it implemented. I'll wait for some more answers here. If it is agreed to add it, I will make a pull request. If not, it was a nice exercise for me to get back into contributing <span aria-label=\"smiley\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f603\" role=\"img\" title=\"smiley\">:smiley:</span></p>",
        "id": 406935297,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702128854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>interesting! I'm curious to know how this is used in practice - does anyone have some code snippets of how they've used this in Roc?</p>",
        "id": 406945896,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1702133321
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is an example:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">calculatePercentageDiff</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span>\n\n<span class=\"err\">#</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Function to calculate the daily percentage change in stock prices</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">calculateDailyPercentageChange</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">calculateDailyPercentageChange</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">stockPrices</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">stockPrices</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">calculatePercentageDiff</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>In <code>F#</code> instead of special map function, there is a <code>List.pairwise</code> function that makes a list of tuples - this way you can use it with map, filter, reduce, etc (more flexible,  but probably also a performance hit):</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">pairwise</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">calculatePercentageDiff</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span>\n\n<span class=\"err\">#</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Function to calculate the daily percentage change in stock prices</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">calculateDailyPercentageChange</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">F64</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">calculateDailyPercentageChange</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">stockPrices</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">stockPrices</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">pairwise</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">calculatePercentageDiff</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>You could also use this to check if a list is sorted:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">pairwise</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"err\">#</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Function to check if a list is sorted in ascending order</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">isSortedAsc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Bool</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">isSortedAsc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">list</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">pairwise</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">all</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">&lt;=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 406956265,
        "sender_full_name": "Artur Domurad",
        "timestamp": 1702141721
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like the idea of adding pairwise! I prefer that over mapAdjacent because it would be more general. For example, you could map or walk over the list of pairs depending on your needs instead of only being able to map.</p>",
        "id": 406956513,
        "sender_full_name": "Isaac Van Doren",
        "timestamp": 1702141975
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't have a strong opinion on if we use pairWise or mapAdjacent. If you want to filter on pairs you could still do it with mapAdjacent:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"p\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">keepIf</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">foo</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I tend to do the same when using map2 sometimes</p>",
        "id": 406958234,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702143587
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think is is a matter of preference which to pick (or both), but I don't have a strong preference</p>",
        "id": 406958292,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702143617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281383\">Richard Feldman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/List.2EmapAdjacent/near/406945896\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>interesting! I'm curious to know how this is used in practice - does anyone have some code snippets of how they've used this in Roc?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I tend to use it with differences most of the time. If I have a list of numbers (either in a variable, or in a pipeline), and I want to calculate the differences between them.<br>\nI think that is the most common use case, as it is called adjacent_difference when used with c++ iterators.</p>\n<p>A code snippet from today's AoC (paraphrased as I am using a phone) was something like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">numbers</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">line</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">split</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\" \"</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">mapTry</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">toI32</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">okOrCrash</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">differences</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">numbers</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">drop1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">numbers</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Here it would have been nice to have the mapAdjacent to not have to name the badly named <code>numbers</code></p>",
        "id": 406958619,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702143966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so one of the tradeoffs I think about with convenience functions like this is: what happens if someone later comes along to read the code and they don't know what the convenience function does, because it's rarely used?</p>",
        "id": 406960648,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1702145714
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>like for example <a href=\"https://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/list-extra/latest/List-Extra#break\">https://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-community/list-extra/latest/List-Extra#break</a></p>",
        "id": 406960777,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1702145860
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281383\">Richard Feldman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/List.2EmapAdjacent/near/406960648\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>so one of the tradeoffs I think about with convenience functions like this is: what happens if someone later comes along to read the code and they don't know what the convenience function does, because it's rarely used?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Totally understandable</p>\n<p>I have had a few situations where I missed it, but to be honest, I have mainly used roc for AoC and similar puzzles, so maybe my experiences are not a proper represenation for the average roc user</p>",
        "id": 406960811,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1702145884
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah I think this is just on the side of the line where I'd rather not have it as a builtin <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 406960837,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1702145902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"497765\">Kilian Vounckx</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/List.2EmapAdjacent/near/406912843\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This can be implemented in pure roc as</p>\n<p><div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">dropFirst</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span>\n</code></pre></div><br>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For what it's worth, this simple implementation actually has a performance pitfall as far as I can tell: it fails to be in-place like<code>List.map</code> when <code>list</code> is uniquely owned and <code>a</code> = <code>b</code>. I can only see how to make an in-place implementation using <code>List.update</code>, which requires that the input and ouput type are the same. Is there a way to make a pure roc implementation which is in-place when <code>a</code> = <code>b</code> but still generic over two type variables? If not, maybe a builtin is warranted?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"err\">#</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">In</span><span class=\"nf\">-</span><span class=\"nv\">place</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">but</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">requires</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">input</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">and</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">output</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">are</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">same</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kr\">type</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacentHelper</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacentHelper</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">when</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">get</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">is</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kt\">Ok</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"nv\">newL</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">update</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">y</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"nv\">mapAdjacentHelper</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">newL</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kt\">Err</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">OutOfBounds</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">dropLast</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 407177118,
        "sender_full_name": "timotree",
        "timestamp": 1702278770
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the missing primitive here is an in-place implementation of</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">mapWithTails</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">mapWithTails</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">mapWithIndex</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">\\</span><span class=\"nv\">elem</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">elem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">dropFirst</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 407177764,
        "sender_full_name": "timotree",
        "timestamp": 1702279019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(For fully general builtin, you would actually want <code>walkMapWithTailsUntil</code> :P)</p>",
        "id": 407178000,
        "sender_full_name": "timotree",
        "timestamp": 1702279103
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Is there a way to make a pure roc implementation which is in-place when a = b but still generic over two type variables?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think that's possible yes. All of the reference counting stuff comes after type specialization. (It has to, because different types have different memory layouts, with pointers to their children in different places.) So the concept of \"type variables\" doesn't exist at that point in the compiler pipeline. All types are concrete.</p>",
        "id": 407209662,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Carroll",
        "timestamp": 1702290374
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But could you define it using existing list builtins? I don't think so</p>",
        "id": 407290240,
        "sender_full_name": "timotree",
        "timestamp": 1702316526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not in a way that avoids reallocation while being fully general.</p>",
        "id": 407291028,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1702316860
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(deleted)</p>",
        "id": 407291166,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1702316921
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cause you need builtin magic to check if the list is unique and the output type is equal in size to the input type if you want it to be fully generic</p>",
        "id": 407291421,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1702317019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess you could also make it inplace if the output type is smaller.</p>",
        "id": 407291449,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1702317033
    }
]